d its present-day incarnations, R. Marie Griffith vividly analyzes Christianity's intricate role in America's obsession with the body, diet, and fitness. As she traces the underpinning of modern-day beauty and slimness ideals—as well as the bigotry against people who are overweight—Griffith links seemingly disparate groups in American history including seventeenth-century New England Puritans, Progressive Era New Thought adherents, and late-twentieth-century evangelical diet preachers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrines. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aProtestantismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican history.  abeauty ideals.  abigotry.  aborn again christians.  achristian dieting.  achristian fitness.  achristianity.  adiet and nutrition.  adiet culture.  adiet history.  adiet literature.  adiet preachers.  adiet programs.  afitness programs.  afood and culture.  anonfiction survey.  anonfiction.  aobesity.  aoverweight populations.  aphysical anthropology.  areligious movements.  areligious perspectives.  asociology.  aspiritual connections.  aspirituality.  atheoretical approach.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021753940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093811340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938113423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938113/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY